 AD-HOCKERY /ad-hok'@r-ee/ [Purdue] n. 1. Gratuitous assumptions made inside
certain programs, esp. expert systems, which lead to the appearance of
semi-intelligent behavior, but are in fact entirely arbitrary. 2.
Special-case code to cope with some awkward input which would otherwise cause
a program to CHOKE, presuming normal inputs are dealt with in some cleaner
and more regular way.